      <hedline>
        <hl1>Racial Bridges, Open and Closed</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Kevin Boyle letter says June 16 article about Smithfield Packing Co, dramatizes need for meaningful labor law reform; says were there a union at Smithfield, management would not be free to intimidate workers and assign jobs by race</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''At a Slaughterhouse, Some Things Never Die'' (''How Race Is Lived in America,'' front page, June 16), dramatizes the need for meaningful labor law reform. Had there been a union at Smithfield Packing Co., foremen would not be free to intimidate workers, and management, checked by plantwide seniority, would not be free to assign  jobs by race. But because the law allows employers to intimidate workers who dare to talk of unionization, Smithfield Packing has become a truly brutal workplace.</p>
        <p>KEVIN BOYLE  South Deerfield, Mass., June 16, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an associate professor of history, University of Massachusetts at Amherst.</p>
      </block>
